  "prompt": "What are some good auto biographies?",
  "response": "There are many compelling autobiographies that offer deep insights into the lives of their authors. Here are some notable ones across various genres and experiences:\n\n1. **\"The Autobiography of Malcolm X\"** by Malcolm X and Alex Haley - A powerful account of the civil rights leader's life, filled with his thoughts on race, identity, and personal transformation.\n\n2. **\"Becoming\"** by Michelle Obama - The former First Lady shares her experiences from childhood through her years in the White House, discussing the challenges and triumphs faced along the way.\n\n3. **\"Long Walk to Freedom\"** by Nelson Mandela - Mandela's inspiring story of his journey from a small village in South Africa to becoming the country's first black president and a global symbol of peace and reconciliation.\n\n4. **\"The Diary of a Young Girl\"** by Anne Frank - A poignant and personal account of a young Jewish girl\u2019s life in hiding during the Holocaust, offering profound insights into human resilience.\n\n5. **\"I Know Why the Caged Bird Sings\"** by Maya Angelou - This classic autobiography details Angelou's early years and her experiences with racism, trauma, and the power of art and literature.\n\n6. **\"Just as I Am\"** by Cicely Tyson - The late iconic actress shares her journey, struggles, and the role of her faith in guiding her throughout her remarkable life and career.\n\n7. **\"The Glass Castle\"** by Jeannette Walls - A memoir about Walls\u2019 unconventional, often chaotic childhood, revealing strength and resilience in the face of hardship.\n\n8. **\"Born a Crime: Stories from a South African Childhood\"** by Trevor Noah - A humorous and poignant exploration of the comedian's upbringing in apartheid South Africa, highlighting issues of identity and race.\n\n9. **\"Educated\"** by Tara Westover - Westover's journey from growing up in a strict and abusive household in rural Idaho to earning a PhD from Cambridge University, emphasizing the importance of education.\n\n10. **\"Open\"** by Andre Agassi - A candid and introspective look into the life of the tennis legend, discussing his challenges and the pressures of fame.\n\nThese autobiographies not only tell the stories of remarkable individuals but also provide valuable lessons and reflections on life, resilience, and the human experience.",
